comments.body:
Attached is a first draft of a way this new type of readiness check could work. The idea I had was that in many cases the way to check a container would be using a container of the same type. In this patch, after container status is retrieved successfully, a readiness check container is requested. The launch context (docker image or tarball, configuration files, environment, etc.) is set up the same way as for the "main" container, except that a different launch command is specified and the resource request is simplified (and optionally a different resource request can be specified). Using the same information for container setup as for the main container greatly simplifies the amount of configuration we need to specify for the readiness check, and it is also a best practice in the case of docker containers since it does not require a separate docker image.

This version of the patch doesn't include documentation updates, but here is an example of how to configure the new type of readiness check:
{noformat}
      "readiness_check": {
        "type": "CONTAINER",
        "properties": {
          "command": "curl http://${COMPONENT_INSTANCE_NAME}.${SERVICE_NAME}.${USER}.${DOMAIN}:8080"
        }
      }
{noformat}

